<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/3af53044cc85a7909172e378d6000b96> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "EEN SCENE UIT DE BALLAD VAN HAMIR HATH : SULTAN ALA-UD-DIN'S BOOGSCHUTTER SCHIET DE DANSERES NEER" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/3af53044cc85a7909172e378d6000b96> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "De voorbereiding voor de oorlog is aan de gang. de Sultan's kamp staat opgesteld tegenpver de bergvesting van Ranthambhor. Om zijn onbevreesde houding te demonstreren, geeft Hamir Hath een dansvorstelling in zijn paleis, ten aanschouw van de Sultan en zijn aanhangers. De danseres draait steeds met de rug naar de Sultan, die deze als een zware belediging neemt. Hij geeft zijn bevel aan zijn beste boogschutter om haar neer te schieten.\r\nSoldaten in westerse uniform, vooral kanonniers, maken ook deel uit van de Sultan's leger. \r\nVan dezelfde serie als 3025-47, 3025-49 t/m 3025-51" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/3af53044cc85a7909172e378d6000b96> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#material> "zwarte lijntekening op papierpapier\r\nThe drawing was made on a sheet of Indian handmade paper. The paper has small charcoal particles, protruding fibres and fragments of blue thread or yarn that were part of the pulp composition and of the papermaking process. They indicate that the paper was made from recycled materials.\r\nThis work belongs to a series of five drawings depicting the Ballad of Amir Hath. On the recto, the primary outline was made with charcoal, the secondary drawing was carried out with red ink and the final outline was drawn with black ink. Some lines were corrected after being concealed with white paint (most likely lead white). The gunner in the forefront is painted with yellow paint The support has been burnished on the recto and verso with two different tools: a wide and a narrow burnished (stone, glass, conch shell, etc).\r\nOn the verso, there are a few lines of handwritten text in Nagari script which describe the scene painted on the recto. A label from the Vogel collection is adhered to in the bottom part and roughly translates what is written above in Nagari script.\r\nDue to the porosity of the paper and the lack of sizing and burnishing, the ink has migrated from the verso to the recto." .
